    <subfield code="a">Lewis Hayden writes: &quot;All classes rich, poor, all colors assemble together in our unfinished church. Prejudice vanishes.&quot; Through Lewis Hayden&apos;s correspondence with Isaac J. Rice, a missionary at Amherstburg, he has learned of Rice&apos;s suffering and his struggles to get a common school education for the colored people. Hayden comments about Isaac J. Rice: &quot;Like yourself, he knows no bounds to love. He is doing more for the real benefit [of] the cause than any one ever in Canada.&quot;</subfield>
